[SPEAKER_00] First, I think that this, what I would call narrowly theological view on the schism, is that sometimes it's used as it happened in vacuum and some kind of pure ideas, in pure world of ideas.

166
00:17:17,000 --> 00:17:23,000
[SPEAKER_00] And it's equally, I think, bad as very materialistic approach, which says it's only economy or whatever.

167
00:17:23,000 --> 00:17:25,000
[SPEAKER_00] So, I think this is one of the temptations.

168
00:17:25,000 --> 00:17:35,000
[SPEAKER_00] Second one is the mentality, sectarian mentality, often a subgroup of theological view, of course, that perhaps the simplest and often fueled by certain self-righteousness is to say,

169
00:17:35,000 --> 00:17:38,000
[SPEAKER_00] OK, we are right and you are wrong, God is on our side.

170
00:17:38,000 --> 00:17:43,000
[SPEAKER_00] Well, God bless you with this position, now you know the truth, and then there is not much to talk.

171
00:17:43,000 --> 00:17:50,000
[SPEAKER_00] Opposite to these are certain modern or postmodern approaches, which somehow move into direction of politically correct vision of history,

172
00:17:50,000 --> 00:17:56,000
[SPEAKER_00] trying to say everything was fine, everything was just fine, there were no problems before the nations, or whatever.

173
00:17:56,000 --> 00:18:07,000
[SPEAKER_00] Another modern problem deriving from this approach is deep relativism, that tends to express itself in impenetrable jargon of scholarly debate that you don't know what they are talking about anymore.

174
00:18:07,000 --> 00:18:10,000
[SPEAKER_00] So, altogether in this, my concluding remarks will be the following:

175
00:18:10,000 --> 00:18:14,000
[SPEAKER_00] It turns out, thus, that certain part of the whole trouble has an obvious face.

176
00:18:14,000 --> 00:18:18,000
[SPEAKER_00] Even very human, to borrow Nietzsche's words, all too human.

177
00:18:18,000 --> 00:18:23,000
[SPEAKER_00] By stating this, I don't want to downscale the schism to the human size only, God forbids.

178
00:18:23,000 --> 00:18:31,000
[SPEAKER_00] Yet, from what I can see, the greatest thinkers, the holiest churchmen of the age, were, and still are, children of their own age, of course.

179
00:18:31,000 --> 00:18:39,000
[SPEAKER_00] The testimony of a great man, both of West and East, who were able to rightfully, without prejudice, judge, of course, abounds.

180
00:18:39,000 --> 00:18:47,000
[SPEAKER_00] Yet, it was often more in the streets of Constantinople, or military camps of the Crusaders, that the future and the destiny of the church was given direction.

181
00:18:47,000 --> 00:18:54,000
[SPEAKER_00] And there is seemingly no hates of thought and spirit that are untouched by the burden of the flesh, by the turbulence of our own days.

182
00:18:54,000 --> 00:19:01,000
[SPEAKER_00] It is thus, perhaps, not entirely inappropriate that we are reminded, before we plunge into the depths of theological speculation,

183
00:19:01,000 --> 00:19:09,000
[SPEAKER_00] or rise to appreciation of the delights of divine liturgy, that we are all fragile, miserable creatures, often unable to recognize good from evil.

184
00:19:09,000 --> 00:19:14,000
[SPEAKER_00] As Christians, of course, we know that this realization is not the end, but the beginning of salvation.

185
00:19:14,000 --> 00:19:23,000
[SPEAKER_00] So, aware of our miserable state, I would end up with the old invocation to most glorious, ever-Virgin Mary, Mother of Christ our God,

186
00:19:23,000 --> 00:19:29,000
[SPEAKER_00] to accept our prayers and present them to Thy Son, our God, that we may proceed in this direction,

187
00:19:29,000 --> 00:19:32,000
[SPEAKER_00] to salvation of our souls and our churches.

188
00:19:32,000 --> 00:19:34,000
[SPEAKER_00] So, thank you very much.

189
00:19:34,000 --> 00:19:36,000
[UNKNOWN] applause

